!important  You can override all the above rules by adding a “!important” after any property
 This should be used sparingly; excessive use of !important can cause confusion within your codebase
  // in css #thing { color: green; } // add the !important option at the end of your declaration; p { color: red !important; }  &lt;!-- in html --&gt; &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; &lt;html&gt; &lt;head&gt; &lt;title&gt;Sample Page&lt;/title&gt; &lt;/head&gt; &lt;body&gt; &lt;p id=&quot;thing&quot;&gt;Will be RED and NOT Green&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/body&gt; &lt;/html&gt;  Here we used the !

&lt;html&gt;, &lt;body&gt;, &lt;head&gt;, &lt;title&gt; The following tags make up the structure of all web pages
 &lt;html&gt;
 Represents the root (top-level element) of an HTML document, so it is also referred to as the root element
 All other elements must be descendants of this element.
  &lt;body&gt;
 Everything inside the body tag is shown inside the browser window  &lt;head&gt;
 Contains information about the page (vs shown on the pages

display  Defines a flex container
inline or block depending on the given value
 .container { display: flex; /* or inline-flex */ }

flex direction  Establishes the main-axis and defines the direction flex items are placed in the flex container
Determines whether the flex items are layed out as either horizontal rows or vertical columns
 .container { flex-direction: row | row-reverse | column | column-reverse; }

